WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.440
Hello, everyone. I am Isabel Zimmerman. I work for a company called Posit. If you're

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:17.280
wondering where you've heard that before, there was a talk from my colleague Hadley

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:24.879
Wickham yesterday. He was one of the keynotes. We are all about R and Python and thinking

00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:32.560
about multilingual teams and how to make their lives easier. I specifically work with MLOps

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:38.959
and I kind of started my career as a software engineer slash data scientist and I worked

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:46.320
a lot deploying models with Kubernetes. Of course, if you know anything about Kubernetes,

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:51.680
it's a little frustrating, so I decided to take out some of my Kubernetes stress with

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:58.400
teaching my dog silly tricks. The first trick I taught was to teach him to sit. When I first

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:03.080
taught him to sit, I call him to stand right in front of me and I tell him to sit and he

00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:07.720
figures it out and I give him a treat. But then I started taking him on walks and bringing

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:13.879
him out into the real world and, you know, he's walking next to me on my side and I would

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:19.480
tell him to sit and he had no idea what I meant. And, of course, the data scientist

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:24.919
in me is like, oh, I overfit my model. I over trained my dog. Because he realized that

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:30.599
I realized that I'd only ever trained him to sit, like, in front of me. Never off to the side.

00:01:31.639 --> 00:01:37.480
And, you know, that's kind of a hard lesson for a data scientist to learn, but all I knew was

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:44.360
I was training for the right outcome to sit. And in my cozy living room, it totally made sense

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.760
and it worked really well. He knew my task and he would sit on command. But when we went out into

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:59.160
the real world on our silly little walks, there was a new set of challenges and he behaved

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:06.360
differently. I realized I needed to, you know, expand my tool set and expand my mindset for

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:12.759
how to train my dog. But this is not a dog training conference. So, I'll tell you this.

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:21.320
The real world value of models oftentimes comes from integrating them into some larger ecosystem.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:27.800
So, my advice for you is to bring your model on a walk. You can learn to operationalize a model

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:37.960
using practices called MLOps. And MLOps is a set of practices to deploy and maintain machine

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:44.600
learning models in production reliably and efficiently. And these practices can be hard.

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:49.479
Especially with the Kubernetes-based models I had started out with, I felt like a lot of the

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:55.720
tools that I was using, I had to be kind of a cloud architect as well as a data scientist.

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:02.119
And I don't think that data scientists should be oblivious to everything in the DevOps or MLOps

00:03:02.119 --> 00:03:08.039
world. But there's definitely a space for tools that help data scientists more effectively

00:03:08.039 --> 00:03:16.279
communicate with their IT or DevOps teams. And these tools can still feel ergonomic for data

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:24.520
scientists. So, I actually changed career paths. And a package called FedEver was made.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:30.759
FedEver is an MLOps tool for data scientists specifically to help them

00:03:31.639 --> 00:03:37.320
version, monitor, and deploy models in production in both R and Python.

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:44.600
And we thought this was really important to build a tool like this because when you start

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:50.839
learning about data science, you see an image that looks something like this. You collect data. You

00:03:50.839 --> 00:03:56.679
understand and clean your data. If you're using R, that's with tools like the tidyverse or data

00:03:56.679 --> 00:04:03.800
table. If you're using Python, that's using tools like Pandas or NumPy or Suba. And then you get to

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:10.199
training and evaluating your model. Once again, in R, you're using tools like tidy models or in

00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:19.239
Python, scikit-learn, PyTorch. And these different tools have best practices built in in a really

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:26.200
ergonomic way. If you're a data scientist, you write code that looks probably something like

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:33.480
this. You're going to load in your data and, you know, select columns or whatever. But in almost

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:39.640
every data science script, you have a line at the top that sets the random C for reproducibility of

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:45.000
your model. And this feels good. People know how to use it. They know it's a best practice of data

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:52.679
science. When you get to training your model, you split it into test and training sets. So,

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.239
you're not giving your model the answers to the questions you're about to ask it beforehand.

00:04:57.959 --> 00:05:03.559
And this is built into the tools we use. And it feels good and it's ergonomic and we know

00:05:03.559 --> 00:05:11.079
that this is a best practice. And then you get into the actual, like, modeling part of your code.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:17.320
And you think about the right feature engineering for the job. And you think about how to train your

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:23.959
model. And maybe putting these together in a pipeline to make sure that they're all, you know,

00:05:23.959 --> 00:05:30.920
organized and running in the right order. And this feels ergonomic and it's part of the tools

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:38.200
you're using. But oftentimes, this is where you start. You know the data science code,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:45.160
but then you realize that working with a larger team, there's more to data science than training

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:51.480
models. You have to think about how you're sharing these models with others that's not emailing job

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:57.480
lib files back and forth. You have to think about maybe this needs to be integrated into a larger

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:03.000
application. How are you going to get the model from your local environment to there? And how do

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.799
you make sure that this model is still performing well a month from now or even a week from now?

00:06:08.440 --> 00:06:14.119
And you realize that these ergonomic practices and the tools that you love to use aren't quite

00:06:14.119 --> 00:06:20.839
enough. And that's where machine learning operations comes in. The project I work on

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:30.359
is to monitor version and deploy models specifically to help complete that circle.

00:06:31.239 --> 00:06:37.880
So, what are some pieces used in MLOps? Most open source projects fall into one or maybe

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:44.279
multiple of these orchestration, experiment tracking, versioning, serving, and monitoring

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:51.559
pieces. Things like orchestration are going to put your models in larger pipelines. Experiment

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:58.440
tracking is going to make sure all the pieces that are going into the model are organized,

00:06:58.519 --> 00:07:04.200
organized. Versioning, serving, and monitoring will go into a little bit deeper right now.

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:13.799
So, whatever helps with versioning, serving, and monitoring. And when people think about

00:07:13.799 --> 00:07:19.079
versioning, a lot of times you're thinking about Git. And we actually version a lot of

00:07:19.079 --> 00:07:25.959
things and mostly very badly. If you think about, you know, you're making a model and

00:07:26.839 --> 00:07:33.480
you train it. You start it out. You saved it as model. Doing a little bit more work with it,

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:40.200
you have model final. And you feel pretty good. But maybe you get new data or you want to try

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:45.320
out a new algorithm and it works better. And then you realize there's actually another iteration.

00:07:45.959 --> 00:07:54.440
And you can see how this data science workflow of versioning locally might not be the right fit.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:08:02.119
We can see that this model final, model final, final doesn't scale for one model,

00:08:02.119 --> 00:08:08.519
let alone tens or hundreds of models. It would be really nice, you know, if we're thinking about

00:08:08.519 --> 00:08:15.239
what we want out of versioning, if these could all live in a central location that we can access,

00:08:15.239 --> 00:08:21.079
but also maybe our teammates. And especially if they could load right into memory and maybe have

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:25.559
a little bit more context where I don't have to guess what model final really means.

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:35.159
And there's actually a secret weapon that the project I work on uses. And this is another

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:42.520
open source library called pins. And pins is also available in Python and R. And it helps you

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:51.159
organize and store your models. And it does this by creating a board. So, the mental model for a

00:08:51.159 --> 00:08:58.440
board is maybe to, like, think of it's a place for your models and then you can pin your models

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:04.520
onto your board. So, it's creating a place for models to be stored. We can see here this is a

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:12.280
temporary board. But this could also be board underscore S3, Azure, GCS for Google Cloud Storage

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:21.400
or Connect, which is Posit's homegrown pro product. So, now that we have a space for our model to go,

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:27.400
we can create a vetiver model object. So, this is a deployable model object because there's

00:09:27.719 --> 00:09:34.919
a lot of information that you have at training time that you can store that's useful from your

00:09:34.919 --> 00:09:41.400
model later. Here, all we're going to put in is our random forest pipeline we made before. And

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:49.799
we're going to give it a name, ads. From there, we can vetiver pin write our temporary board.

00:09:50.679 --> 00:09:53.799
We're going to put our vetiver model V onto the temporary board.

00:09:55.559 --> 00:10:04.039
And with that, we have some more context as well. Not only is this organized within the board for

00:10:04.039 --> 00:10:09.719
us automatically, we can see a description of the model. We can see the size of it,

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:16.280
what kind of file it is, and some other required packages. And if we wanted to take this a step

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:21.880
further, we could even give our model more context. So, we could save a tiny little piece

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:26.440
of our training data to better debug when things go wrong in production.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:33.880
If you think about it like a puzzle, it's a lot easier to make a puzzle when you know what the

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:38.760
finished product is supposed to look like. And this is essentially giving that finished product

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:45.159
to our model. And it's pretty easy to add this in. This is the same line of code before,

00:10:45.159 --> 00:10:50.919
but we just have one more argument. P type data for prototype data. And we're going to give it

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:59.400
our X train. But we want to also think more holistically about tracking and versioning

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:05.000
models. And there's the idea of something called a model card. And model cards are to make sure

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.520
you're not only making good statistical models, but good ethical models that you've thought

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:17.960
really wholly about. Model cards are kind of like recipes. You know, you never know as much

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:22.679
about your cake of, like, oh, this batter is a little watery or something like that,

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:29.239
than when you're making it. Model cards use that same mental model. They want to make sure that

00:11:29.239 --> 00:11:36.119
you can have a designated place to write down all the information you know when training your model

00:11:36.119 --> 00:11:41.159
that you can look back at later. So, that summary statistics, that's general documentation,

00:11:41.159 --> 00:11:47.960
as well as nods to fairness. So, we saw this line of code earlier as well.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:55.000
Vetiver pin write, our V vetiver model onto our model board. But there's actually a little

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.679
informative message that pops up after. And you can read the informative message or you can

00:12:00.679 --> 00:12:04.440
do whatever software engineer does and just copy and paste the code and run it and see what happens.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:12.760
This vetiver.model card. And when you run this vetiver.model card, there's a Quarto document

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:21.479
that is generated. And Quarto is a flavor of Markdown that is used for documentation that you

00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:28.919
can actually run live code in. My slides were made in Quarto, as well as my blog is made in Quarto.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:34.520
If you're interested in learning more, tomorrow there is a talk on Quarto by my colleague Tom

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:43.320
Mock to explore the wonderful world of this new tool. So, if you open up your Quarto card,

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:48.119
you can see there's some information that's automatically generated for you.

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:53.960
And that's things like, you know, it's a scikit-learn pipeline. It's a model using four

00:12:53.960 --> 00:13:02.119
features. Here's when the model was created. And if you scroll down, there's also some information

00:13:02.119 --> 00:13:07.479
on that input data prototype. So, this model has got four features looking at houses,

00:13:08.359 --> 00:13:13.799
as well as a quantitative analysis looking at things like mean absolute error, mean squared

00:13:13.799 --> 00:13:20.679
error, and so on. And if you scroll all the way to the end, there's also places for you to document

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:27.719
ethical considerations that you have and caveats and recommendations that you've uncovered while

00:13:27.719 --> 00:13:33.080
training this model. And, of course, if you don't really have information for either of these off

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:40.440
the top of your head, it's important to keep these on the model card because imprecise or incomplete

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:46.679
information is better than none at all. My dad had always told me growing up that

00:13:46.679 --> 00:13:51.559
if you haven't written it down, you haven't thought it out. And model cards are a great

00:13:51.559 --> 00:13:57.159
place for you to write out all of the things that you've been thinking about at training time for

00:13:57.159 --> 00:14:05.000
your model. So, we know about the beginning of this life cycle, and we know about what

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:12.599
versioning a model is. And so, what happens when we have to deploy it? So, deployment means a lot

00:14:12.599 --> 00:14:18.679
of different things for a lot of different people. But the way that our team has defined

00:14:18.679 --> 00:14:27.799
it as is bringing a model off a local laptop into some sort of other architecture. We do this by

00:14:27.799 --> 00:14:34.039
creating a REST API endpoint. It makes your software engineer friends happy because they

00:14:34.039 --> 00:14:38.679
are pretty robust and testable, and it makes your data scientists happy because there's a lot of

00:14:38.679 --> 00:14:45.640
great tools to help you spin them up and maintain them. To do this with Vediver, if you want to run

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:53.960
an API locally, our Vediver model named V from earlier can be put into a Vediver API and you can

00:14:53.960 --> 00:15:02.840
run it. But, of course, the end goal of this is to not have a local API endpoint. So, if you were

00:15:02.840 --> 00:15:10.679
to want to deploy this onto our pro products, which is Connect, you could set up a Connect server

00:15:10.679 --> 00:15:17.080
and then just send it a model board, the name of your model, and then the specific version that

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:24.440
you'd like to deploy. And it will do the rest of the work for you. If you're looking to move this

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:33.640
into maybe a Docker file or anywhere that ingests Docker files, such as AWS or Azure or Google Cloud

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:40.359
Storage or Google Cloud Platform, you can do this in two different steps. First is to write out an

00:15:40.359 --> 00:15:48.520
app.py file. As long as you're giving your board and pin name to this function, it will generate

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:57.239
this app.py file for you and get you at least most of the way there. And then you can write

00:15:57.239 --> 00:16:04.919
out a Docker file and send in the app.py file that you have just created. And then this Docker file

00:16:04.919 --> 00:16:11.000
will be written out for you that's usable out of the box, but that you can also edit to customize

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:17.799
for your own deployment. And that's what deployment looks like using FedEver. These

00:16:17.799 --> 00:16:24.039
helper functions are really made to make it feel accessible to get this model off your laptop,

00:16:24.039 --> 00:16:28.039
or at least to have a Docker file in hand to pass off to somebody else.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:37.880
Now, once your model is off your laptop, a data scientist's work is not done. And monitoring

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:42.119
means something unique in this context. We're not necessarily monitoring

00:16:43.799 --> 00:16:49.960
things like CPU usage or runtime. Here we're specifically looking at the statistical

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:58.280
properties of the input data or predictions. And FedEver helps this out with a few

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:04.520
helper functions. I won't go too deep into them right now. But it essentially will help you

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:10.359
compute metrics over certain rolling window timeframes that you specify. Here it'll be for

00:17:10.359 --> 00:17:17.719
one week. It'll help you pin your metrics, especially if you get into that awkward situation

00:17:17.719 --> 00:17:24.119
where some of the dates overlap. FedEver pin metrics will sort that out for you,

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:31.719
overwrite with the newest data if necessary. And then finally, FedEver also helps you

00:17:31.719 --> 00:17:37.079
plot your metrics in the same format that is coming out of FedEver compute metrics

00:17:37.959 --> 00:17:45.079
to get kind of an out of the box quick peek into how your model is performing.

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:54.280
And this is really important to track. If you are not monitoring your model, you are oblivious to

00:17:54.280 --> 00:18:00.199
model decay. And of course, that makes sense. You need some data to make sure you're doing the right

00:18:00.199 --> 00:18:10.520
thing. But this is especially important because models break quietly. They'll continue to run and

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:18.199
really just proudly give you very wrong answers. Even if your accuracy is like zero percent.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:24.520
Whereas on the other side, you know, applications will often give you big red Xs. Models will

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:31.400
continue to give you bad answers. So, if you're not monitoring your model, you are oblivious to

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:40.599
this decay. And that has completed our cycle in a very fast way. We have gone over versioning a

00:18:40.599 --> 00:18:47.959
model, deploying a model, and monitoring a model. But if we think about FedEver as a whole,

00:18:47.959 --> 00:18:52.520
why should I be excited about FedEver? Well, why am I excited about FedEver?

