and funky this is, I would love to hop on Discord and chat with you about that. It was so cool.

00:23:47.319 --> 00:23:53.800
Cool. Thank you. And just as a reminder, there is on Discord a channel called

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:59.800
Talks-Discussions, which Isabel and other speakers will be monitoring.

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:07.800
A question from Patrick. It looks like Vetiver is a decentralized version of some of these

00:24:07.800 --> 00:24:13.640
other platforms that require spinning up an on-prem or a cloud server to track this stuff.

00:24:13.640 --> 00:24:24.359
Is that true? So, let me make sure I answer this correctly. To have something that is

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:32.119
shareable with your larger team, a lot of times the right tool is to be on-prem or in a cloud

00:24:32.119 --> 00:24:39.560
server that's using Docker files. So, Vetiver is able to bring your model onto those different

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:47.640
places as well. I think one of the exciting things that we like to play around with with Vetiver is

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:52.199
it makes it really easy to spin things up locally. So, that might be where you're feeling this

00:24:53.079 --> 00:25:00.359
decentralized bit. And that's really important because a lot of times when you're testing or

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:08.680
development versions are very different from what your deployed versions feel like, things break

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:17.319
very quickly. So, being able to quickly, rapidly prototype a small API and scale it safely is

00:25:17.319 --> 00:25:24.920
something that Vetiver focuses on a lot. So, yes, it can be easy to put up locally in a really

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:32.599
decentralized way. But it also makes it easy to ship it to an on-prem or a cloud server instance.

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:42.599
And a question from Neil. How does Vetiver compare with MLflow? When would you prefer

00:25:42.599 --> 00:25:51.479
one over the other? Yes, this is a great question. So, there are a lot of ML ops tools out there.

00:25:51.479 --> 00:25:58.680
And MLflow is one that we've looked at a lot. And what they've done really well is they have a lot

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:05.719
of investment into experiment tracking. So, if you are looking to track all of the hyper parameters

00:26:06.599 --> 00:26:10.680
that you've used when training your model, like every single time you've trained your model,

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:17.079
that's something that MLflow does very, very well. So, if you're looking for experiment tracking,

00:26:17.079 --> 00:26:24.920
I think that's a good place to go. If you're looking for making APIs quickly and safely,

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:29.640
I think that's where Vetiver shines, kind of for the reasons I just mentioned. Because it is

00:26:30.599 --> 00:26:37.800
like three lines of code to do a very simple spin up a model within an API. So, I'd say if

00:26:37.800 --> 00:26:41.959
you're looking for experiment tracking, MLflow is a great place to start.

00:26:41.959 --> 00:26:45.959
If you're looking for deployment of APIs, Vetiver might be your better option.

